    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_307999"><b><font size="5"><font color="PaleTurquoise"><div align="center">BIRTH OF A UNICORN</div></font></font></b><br />
<font size="2"><div align="center">by Sandra “Raya” Bell</div></font><br />
<br />
<br />
<font size="3">Patryll shifted on the uncomfortable stone bench, waiting for his name to be called.  His first visit to Shemara and already he had done something to annoy the authorities.  He hadn’t thought he’d done anything other than gawk like an orc at the tall buildings and broad boulevards of the high elf city…but who knew the minds of high elves.  He wondered if he had time to just run out and make sure Kiria was okay.  He probably hadn’t better risk it; he didn’t want them any more out for his hide than they already were.<br />
<br />
“Patryll Caelthar, stand forth!” the guard called.<br />
<br />
Patryll stood up, adjusting his short rider’s cloak around his shoulder, and looked enquiringly at the high elf.<br />
<br />
“Follow me,” the guard said gruffly.  Patryll fell in step behind the tall, well-armed elf and marched down a huge hallway of marble and delicately veined stone.  He couldn’t help stopping in amazement at real windows along the exterior wall…with real glass looking out onto the sea.  Most buildings in Shemara looked out onto the sea.  To tell the truth, all that seascape made Patryll a bit queasy, but it sure was pretty to look at for short periods of time.<br />
<br />
“Come along, youngster,” the guard said, looking back at Patryll and hiding a smile.<br />
<br />
“Sorry,” Patryll said, almost skipping in his haste to catch up.<br />
<br />
“So…uh…what’s this all about?” he asked, addressing the guard’s back.  “I didn’t think I broke any of the rules, but since I don’t know them all, there is a good chance that I did break one of them…but I didn’t mean to…I just came to the city to find my mother a present for the Festival of the Unicorn days in our village.  And I found one—Shemarans make the most beautiful necklaces, although I was sorely tempted to buy one of the halfling’s wooden carvings down the street a ways.  I know my horse snitched an apple from the fruit vendor’s stand, but I stopped and paid for it, so that’s not it.”  He coughed and waited, then said, “Is it?”<br />
<br />
The guard didn’t reply, and Patryll was too busy talking to notice another half smile on the man’s face. He always talked more than he should when he was nervous.  His mother sometimes wondered aloud whether he was part human, with all his prattling.  And he’d never outgrown it, not even at the ripe old age of twenty years.  Of course that was almost a baby in elf years, but his part human side was full-grown adult.  Patryll had studied human history and he knew about these things, and anyhow his great grandmother HAD been part human.<br />
<br />
The guard stopped at a heavy, carved, oaken door and opened it for Patryll.  “Have a seat in here,” he said.  “Her Holiness will be with you shortly.  Try not to break anything.”  He closed the door with a grin.<br />
<br />
Flushing, Patryll sat down on the bench in the small waiting room and looked at the hangings on the stone wall.  They were pretty but he wasn’t really interested in hangings.  No one at Verean had wall hangings—they had wood carvings or portraits drawn right on the baked-clay walls.  He cracked his knuckles one by one and smiled, thinking of how his mother winced every time he did that.  It felt good though, as if it were releasing energy from his hands like a healer.<br />
<br />
Suddenly the inner door opened and he jumped to his feet.  In the doorway stood a beautiful woman with long white hair and green eyes.  Her gown was some velvety stuff of a purplish hue, clasped at the waist by a golden belt from which hung a ceremonial short sword.  He couldn’t guess her age because she didn’t look any age.  The white hair was common enough among high elves and didn’t necessarily mean old age like it did with humans and Huramesti elves.<br />
<br />
The woman spoke in a soft, husky voice, “Come in, Patryll Caelthar,” she said.  “I am Emerald Verity, battle cleric of Shemara and keeper of the Maker’s temple.  I hope didn’t mind waiting.  I had urgent things to attend to.”<br />
<br />
“N-no, my lady,” Patryll said.  “I don’t mind waiting for you.”  He felt himself flushing again, and the woman laughed lightly.<br />
<br />
“That is a very graceful compliment, Patryll.  Please.  Sit down.”  She indicated a carved chair across a desk.  She sat behind the desk and looked him straight in the eye.<br />
<br />
“I’m sorry if I did anything wrong,” Patrynn said, not quite able to meet her eyes.  “I didn’t know—was just trying to get a present for my mother in time for the Unicorn Festival back in Verean… my horse, her name is Kiria, got hungry and snitched an apple.  I wasn’t watching because I was in a hurry to get the present and get started home before it got dark.  It’s the Evil One’s own time getting in or out of Shemara after dark because all the streets look alike and…”<br />
<br />
He trailed off at the woman’s amused smile.  Then he noticed that her eyes weren’t smiling.  They were serious, and soon her mouth joined her eyes in a serious look.<br />
<br />
“You did nothing wrong, young Patryll,” she said.  “I have an urgent mission to be undertaken, and you may be the only one here who can accomplish it.”<br />
<br />
Now, THAT was more like it.  Patryll sat up a little straighter and flicked an imaginary speck off his brown tunic.<br />
<br />
“I will do everything in my power to help you, my lady.  What do you need?”<br />
<br />
“The village of Lerona is a four-day ride from here, but it can be made in three by an expert rider with a fast horse,” she began.  “The only way to make it in that time is to take the route directly through the Nimreth Forest.”<br />
<br />
Suddenly, Patryll became all business.  She was now talking about things he knew.  He nodded to indicate he was listening.<br />
<br />
“We received word a few days ago from some refugees that Lerona was set upon and torched by what seemed to be goblin mercenaries.  Lerona is an agricultural village, not equipped—mentally or physically—for battle, and was overrun by these soldiers.  What is worse, after the goblins left, which was strange in itself, the remaining villagers found out the hard way that their only source of water, a well in the center of town, had been poisoned.  The villagers are now not only unprotected and weak from this cowardly attack, but they have no water.”  She stopped, gauging her next words.<br />
<br />
Patryll merely nodded again and waited for her to continue.<br />
<br />
“We did the most prudent thing.  We sent two wagons filled with casks of pure water to fill the most immediate need, along with a potion created by one of our most powerful mages that will clear the water of any poison known to elfinkind.<br />
<br />
<div align="center"><img src="http://www.fantasyfic.com/blue_unicorn.gif" border="0" alt="" /> <img src="http://www.fantasyfic.com/blue_unicorn.gif" border="0" alt="" /> <img src="http://www.fantasyfic.com/blue_unicorn.gif" border="0" alt="" /></div><br />
“Unfortunately,” the Lady continued,  “our two wagons and escort and drivers were set upon by the Kor brethren, possibly of the Nimreth Forest Clan.  Nearly all our contingent was slain, the water barrels smashed, and the potion presumably stolen.”  She had named the black brethren in the old tongue, indicating the seriousness of the situation.<br />
<br />
Patryll gasped.  “Why are the black brethren raiding high elfin wagons?  I thought there was a peace between the two.  I know the top Kor elder of the Nimreth Forest Clan has been talking to the elder of our village as well.  They talked long into the night, but no decision had been reached by the time I left to come here.”<br />
<br />
“An interesting question,” the lady said, “and one to which we hope to find an answer.  As far as we knew, there were similar negotiations going on in Lerona. However, that will have to wait.  Someone must get through to Lerona with the potion.  That someone needs to be a rider beyond compare with a horse as fast as the wind.  The potion takes twenty-four hours to work, on top of a maximum of three days to get there.  If the rescuer takes as long as four full days, there will be no point in going, because there will be no survivors left.”  <br />
<br />
Patryll nodded solemnly, knowing what was coming next.<br />
<br />
“We high elves at Shemara are mariners.  Give us a ship and any star to steer by and we are without equal, but we do not have the expertise to complete this mission, not even with our fastest rider.  The fruit vendor, whose apples your horse sampled, came to me with the story that a Huramesti plains rider and his horse were visiting Shemara, and I sent my guards to find you.”  She stood and came around the desk, beside Patryll.  He turned to face her, swallowing at her nearness.  “Will you undertake this mission, Patryll?”<br />
<br />
“Yes,” he said without hesitation.  “Kiria is rested and well fed.  We can leave immediately.”<br />
<br />
“Thank you,” she said.  “It will be dangerous but we are hoping that a single rider on a fast horse will be able to outrun anything the black brethren OR the goblins can muster.  May the Maker go with you.”<br />
<br />
In less than fifteen minutes, Patryll had leaped upon Kiria, the potion securely stowed in his saddle roll, a small supply of healing ointments and bandages packed around it, along with a small portion of trail food for Patryll to eat along the way.<br />
<br />
Emerald, for that was the lady’s name, had briefed him on the quickest route to Lerona from Shemara, which unfortunately led right through the thick of Nimreth Forest.  The name suited it for, in the old tongue, Nimreth meant “deep arcane” and Patryll knew the forest was deep, dangerous and mysterious.  He had been to the edge of the forest many times, since Verean was just a few hours from the Forest.  He had even entered the woods on a dare from his friends, who were taunting each other as boys often do.  But he had never gone deeply into the Nimreth Forest, for he would have earned a very stern look from his father and a sorrowful look from his mother, both of which cut more to the quick than a birch whip would have flayed his hide.<br />
<br />
He knew the shortcut from Shemara to the edge of the Forest, and he leaned over Kiria’s black silken mane and whispered to her in the old tongue, “Shather, Tae – fly like the wind, beloved.”  Kiria flicked her ears back as if to hear him better.  Instantly, she leaped forward from her comfortable lope to the amazing flash of speed that all Huramesti horses had in reserve.  Kiria had been with Patryll since he had turned twelve, a birthday present from his father, and all the more precious to him since his revered father had been killed by the black brethren two years later.  Patryll would even have slept with her out in the stable if his mother had let him.  And sometimes when she wasn’t looking, he snuck in and slept on the ***** in Kiria’s stall anyway.<br />
<br />
He was proud of her now.  Her feet tapped a rhythm that ate up the distance.  She may have been old as horses go, but she could still outrun most of the youngsters in his elven plains home.  Patryll had been sure to care for her well, and she retained her youthful demeanor and performance.  Now he knew better than to distract her by patting her neck, so merely concentrated on giving her the minimum guidance she needed to stay directed towards Nimreth.<br />
<br />
Crouched behind her head, he made himself as small as possible to cut wind resistance down.  He tucked his legs behind him so that he was almost lying flat on Kiria’s back.  And the wind flew by like the ghost of mist, as Kiria’s strong legs ate up the miles.<br />
<br />
As nightfall approached, the horse and her rider drew near the edge of the Nimreth Forest.  Kiria slowed to a canter, a trot, and then a walk.  She was blowing a bit, and Patryll approved her initiative in walking down the blow, as they called it in his village.  The Huramesti folk, shorter than the high elves, but long and lean as elves went, were practiced in all the ways of a horse.  Their patron deity was Raer, the Unicorn, Beloved Steed and Companion to the Maker, and it was every Huramesti youth’s hope to find a unicorn and tame it.  It was said that no mortal could command a unicorn, that all unicorns were under the bidding of Raer, but this didn’t stop young Huramestians from hoping. <br />
<br />
Patryll eyed the forest with a shudder.  His every instinct warned him to stay away from that darkened woods.  The breeze drifting towards him from the treeline was full of the odor of earth mysteries…molding vegeta-tion, crushed pine needles, sap-filled spruce, ancient bearded oak, pale poplar and leafy ash…all smells that bespoke mystery and unease.  But he couldn’t avoid the forest.  To go around it would take another half a day.  He didn’t have half a day to spare.  He had made up some time on the dash from Shemara to the Nimreth Forest, but the slower going through the woods would likely eat up that extra time.<br />
<br />
He urged Kiria into the woods.  She was nervous and her ears flicked back and forth as she tried to pick up any sound of danger.  Her soft nose snorted with small explosive discharges of air.  Patryll leaned for-ward and petted her neck.  She was picking her way with care but not care enough.  Off balance on the uneven ground, she stumbled badly on a rotten log covered with moss…one front leg plunging through the decomposing wood to the hollow beneath it, the other scrabbling on solid ground.  Patryll fell forward over her neck and she frantically scrambled with her rear legs, trying to back up so she could pull her foot out of its trap.<br />
<br />
Patryll jumped to his feet, unmindful of the trickle of blood oozing down his right cheek from a shallow cut on his scalp.  He ran forward and seized Kiria’s imprisoned leg.  The horse gave a scream of pain as the foot came loose and she thrust back on her haunches, overbalancing and falling over.  Patryll knelt beside her, a sick feeling growing in the pit of his stomach.  Kiria’s foot was swelling just at the hock.  She looked up at Patryll with one eye, as if she was imploring him to help her.  Her nostrils distended and she breathed in and out painfully.<br />
<br />
Patryll’s throat choked with anguish.  Her ankle was either broken or badly sprained, amounting to the same thing in the end.  He laid a hand on her brow and smoothed the silken mane away from her eyes.  “You won’t be able to stand on that foot, my Kiria,” he mourned.  “If we were at home, then I would make you comfortable and bathe it with poultices, then splint it and teach you how to walk on three legs.  And I would feed you grain by my hand.”  He bit his lip and thought frantically for a solution.  The lives of the people of an entire village depended on him.  He had to go on…find another steed if he could.  But he couldn’t leave Kiria here to suffer by herself, at the mercy of the wild things of the forest.  He brushed away a tear that had escaped to roll down his cheek.  He thought his heart might break.  Kiria watched him, as if she under-stood the turmoil he was in.  She had stopped the blowing snorts of fear, and only the erratic rise and fall of her flanks showed how much pain she was in.<br />
<br />
The least he could do was find a way that would be painless.  He would stay with her until she had passed on to the fields of Raer.  He could put an arrow in her…at the base of her spine.  With her lying on her side like that, it would be an awkward angle.  He might try for her great heart, but it was covered over by the uninjured off leg.  Thus, he would have to stand close to her and she would see her beloved boy killing her.<br />
<br />
<div align="center"><img src="http://www.fantasyfic.com/blue_unicorn.gif" border="0" alt="" /> <img src="http://www.fantasyfic.com/blue_unicorn.gif" border="0" alt="" /> <img src="http://www.fantasyfic.com/blue_unicorn.gif" border="0" alt="" /></div><br />
Patryll had never felt such pain in his life.  He decided it would have to be by his hunting knife…a swift slash to the great artery at her neck and her heart’s blood would drain rapidly…there would be little pain.  He walked away from Kiria needing some time to pull himself together and steel himself for the act.  First, he had to stop the flood of wetness on his cheeks, blinding him from his task.<br />
<br />
Time was wasting.  Peoples’ lives hung in the balance of his decision.  He scrubbed the palm of his hand roughly across his eyes, withdrew his large, bone-handled hunting knife and moved back towards Kiria.  Kneeling beside her, he whispered a song of love in the old language, and her rasping breathing calmed.  She even flicked one ear back to listen to him.  He tried to explain to her what he had to do and why, but the words caught in his throat.  He sat for a few moments, stroking her satin neck, silent, lost in his grief…<br />
<br />
…which is why he didn’t see the light appear in the huge oak tree to his left.  It shimmered and grew, finally giving off a faint rustling sound.  It was the whisper of leaves that brought Patryll’s head up.  He stared at the light as it moved from the tree to hover close to Kiria’s nose.  The old horse didn’t even start.  Instead, she closed her eyes.<br />
<br />
Patryll was speechless, an uncommon occurrence.  The light grew and finally burst like a child’s soap bubble, revealing within a dainty female, scantily clad.  Patryll’s mouth dropped open.  He jumped to his feet.  He had never seen a dryad before, logical since dryads mostly lived in forests.<br />
<br />
“Why do you cry, boy?” the dryad asked, cocking her head to one side like a puzzled bird.<br />
<br />
“I…that is…my horse...”  Between grief and confusion, he couldn’t get the words out.  He merely stepped aside so the girl could see the stricken horse lying on the ground.<br />
<br />
“Ah, I see.”  Her voice softened, and the unspoken sympathy almost undid Patryll.  He took a deep breath, holding back his tears, not wanting to cry in front of this vision of beauty.<br />
<br />
“And you weep for this horse?” she asked.<br />
<br />
“Yes,” Patryll said.  “Kiria is my friend, and her ankle is injured badly.  I must put her out of her pain and carry on with my mission.”  He said the last very softly as if he didn’t want to hear it himself.<br />
<br />
“You have a mission.”  It was a statement more than a question, but he nodded anyway.<br />
<br />
Again the dryad cocked her head to one side, her pale yellow hair swinging like a soft cloud down her shoulders.  This time it seemed as if she were listening to something he couldn’t hear.  He waited politely, thinking, however, that he must do the deed quickly before he lost his resolve.  Yet, he didn’t want to do it in front of the girl…didn’t want her to see this little murder.  Anxiety on top of grief and confusion churned inside him and he felt ill.  Somehow he had to do the deed and find another mount to complete his task.<br />
<br />
“You will need a mount to complete your task?” she said.  Patryll started.  It seemed she was a mind reader too.<br />
<br />
“Yes,” he said.<br />
<br />
“Then, Raer says you shall have one.”<br />
<br />
Patryll’s eyes flew open.  The Maker’s steed—and the herd stallion of the magic-blessed unicorns of Athero—was involving himself in his, Patryll’s, doings?  He could find nothing to say.  He merely watched as the girl gathered the sparkling air around her into one big ball of energy.  She handled it lightly, as if it were a child’s hoop, and moved it over to Kiria.  The mare opened, then closed, her eyes again with a sigh, her breathing eased.  The light flowed from the dryad’s hands like water from a jug and formed a pool of light around Kiria’s entire body.  The brightness increased until Patryll had to shade his eyes from the glare.  It was brighter than the sun on a hot day, yet bore the silvery color of the light of the moon.  Where it seemed to touch Kiria’s body, it sparkled and sank through her hide…until Patryll couldn’t tell where the light left off and Kiria began.<br />
<br />
After what seemed like a very long time but in reality was only a few minutes, the light dimmed and then faded gently away.  Kiria heaved herself up onto her feet with little effort, as if there was nothing wrong with her ankle at all.  Patryll gazed at her with concern, noting that the ankle seemed as sturdy and slender as it ever had been.  As he watched, still dazzled by the brightness of the light, the girl came forward, holding an oak branch in her hand.  She stood on tiptoe and placed the end of the branch firmly on Kiria’s forehead.  Murmuring some words in a tongue Patryll didn’t recognize, she held the branch for a moment, then stepped back.<br />
<br />
To Patryll’s astonishment, the branch shimmered, then straightened and narrowed.  It crowned Kiria’s head at a point equidistant between the two ears on the horizontal and between the end of the eye cavity and the beginning of the ear on the vertical.  It was a perfect spiral horn… appearing to be made of polished bone, or ivory, or perhaps white wood.  He didn’t know.  Incongruously, a small, perfectly shaped, oak leaf dangled from the tip of the horn.<br />
<br />
To compound his amazement, Kiria, who had been a magnificent bay color from the time of her birth, was now a glowing gray-white.  Her beautiful, well-shaped head, with large, intelligent eyes, were this same gray-white, and the mane sweeping between her forward pricked ears and over her muscled neck and shoulder, was a solid silvery gray.  Her hooves were a dainty, dark silver, like the buckles that the halfling metalsmiths made and sold in Shemara.  <br />
<br />
He turned, speechless, to the girl and spread his hands in question.<br />
<br />
She laughed lightly.  “Do not be afraid.  This is the spirit of your horse…united with the power of Raer.  Love has made this possible.  You must remember one thing though.”<br />
<br />
Patryll nodded uncertainly.<br />
<br />
The girl stood on tiptoe and plucked the leaf from the end of the horn.  She held it out to Patryll.  He took it and gazed at it in bewilderment.<br />
<br />
“Unicorns are the steeds of the gods and no mortal can possess them. The transformation will be complete when the leaf loses its green color in three full moons from now.  By the time the leaf loses its color you must release the unicorn from your bonds. Do this by dropping the leaf to the ground. When this happens, the unicorn will know you no more and will leave you behind.  The soul of your horse is bound now to the spirit of Raer and will owe her allegiance to him.  If you keep the leaf in your possession when it loses its color, the unicorn will die.”<br />
<br />
Patryll found his tongue.  “But what will happen to Kiria…?”<br />
<br />
The light around the girl faded, and as it grew softer, the outline of the beautiful girl became transparent.  The last he saw before she disappeared completely was a cheerful smile.  He turned and looked searchingly at the unicorn.  The wide black eyes regarded him soberly.  He could not see Kiria in the unicorn’s eyes, but it didn’t feel all that different.  He couldn’t think of that now.<br />
<br />
Quickly refastening the riding gear, he adjusted it to the slimmer dimen-sions of this steed, gathering up the pouch containing the priceless potion.  He wrestled mentally with the name he would call the steed aloud and in his mind.  He finally decided that Ukiria was a happy combination of unicorn and Kiria, and it sounded well on his tongue.   Jumping up onto the light plains saddle, he urged the mare deep into the wood, using the setting sun behind his back to guide him in the right direction.<br />
<br />
The encroaching darkness turned the already gloomy forest to near black.  He had contemplated making a short camp to protect the…he adjusted the name in his mind…protect Ukiria against losing her footing again.  As with all the various races of elves on Athero, Patryll had keen eyesight, which could penetrate all but the darkest black.  Even here, he could see faintly the images of the trees and branches he brushed by, but he was unsure of Ukiria’s capabilities.  The old Kiria had keen vision for a horse, but this total dark would have been beyond her ability.  He needn’t have worried, though.  Ukiria was as sure-footed in the forest gloom as Kiria would have been on the rolling plains under a full moon.<br />
<br />
Finally satisfied that Ukiria not only knew what she was doing but apparently knew the way, Patryll congratulated himself on finally having the moon goddess smile on him and his mission.  Mentally going over the plains rider’s hymn with its lovely soft words, he stilled his mind and dozed in the saddle.<br />
<br />
<div align="center">* * * *</div><br />
Jisvold melted from one shadow to the next, upwind of the traveler.  His keen eyes detected the glow of the steed and he was curious.  He had been following the Huramesti from the moment he had entered the Nimreth Forest.  The word left a bad taste in his mouth and he spat it out—Huramesti, the whining horse strider elves, that groveled and clawed a living on their miserable, barren plains.  Jisvold sensed the unease that the rider felt, and he exulted.  The Gysse Kor were the lords of the forest.  He knew every leaf and every trail in these woods.  Following the dog of a rider, he knew from the path he was taking that he was heading for the vile plains village of Lerona.<br />
<br />
He had seen the horse fall and was about to dash in and finish the brat, when the light had stopped him.  He watched the dryad…he wouldn’t admit it to himself but he was a little afraid of the tree sprites…and swore beneath his breath as the horse was replaced with one of accursed Raer’s fillies.  What could a wet-behind-the-ears Huramesti brat have possibly done to warrant Raer’s intervention?  No mortal could subdue a unicorn, and the last he had heard of, the Huramesti were still mortal; they shed the same color blood as the other elves of Athero.  His lips thinned in a grimace, his version of a smile at his little joke.<br />
<br />
Since the brat’s destination was unarguably Lerona, the only place he could find the path out of the Forest was the Clearing.  Jisvold knew exactly where he would ambush them.  Moving swiftly, running without effort, he dodged the trees, not allowing the tiniest crackle of a twig to betray his presence. <br />
<br />
<div align="center">* * * *</div><br />
The journey was long but Ukiria seemed not to tire.  Patryll followed the Huramesti pattern of dozing for a while, then waking for a while, and repeating the pattern.  Huramesti youth were trained to travel long distances and be refreshed by whatever sleep they managed to get.<br />
<br />
Following one of the dozing periods, after hours of traveling through the dark forest, Patryll forced himself to stay awake.  He felt that the sleep he was having was not refreshing.  He wasn’t sure why, but he felt restless and wary.  Perhaps it was the uncertainty of Kiria’s fate and the dire urgency of his mission.  Once, he thought he heard something, something so faint he finally decided he had been imagining things.  He supposed that forests were alive at night with rustling sounds of night creatures and trapped breezes.  Nimreth Forest was almost silent, save for the occasional hooting moan of an owl.<br />
<br />
<div align="center"><img src="http://www.fantasyfic.com/blue_unicorn.gif" border="0" alt="" /> <img src="http://www.fantasyfic.com/blue_unicorn.gif" border="0" alt="" /> <img src="http://www.fantasyfic.com/blue_unicorn.gif" border="0" alt="" /></div><br />
After tuning his senses to the surroundings and the trail behind and ahead, he was satisfied that all seemed well.  He dug into the food pouch that Emerald had given him and chewed on a piece of dried trail meat, seasoned and smoked the Huramesti way.  He had stopped being surprised at the ingenuity of the high elves.<br />
<br />
When he had finished eating, he unstoppered the waterskin and took a few deep swallows.  Then he leaned over the neck of the steed, brushing his hand lightly downward.  “Are you hungry, girl?  Want to stop and graze for a bit or catch a few mouthfuls of water?”<br />
<br />
Ukiria shook her head in an almost human denial and sped up, forcing Patryll to duck under some low hanging branches.  He chuckled.  That seemed like Kiria, right enough.  She had been a bossy mare, who never had trouble making her preferences known.<br />
<br />
Patryll kept a watchful eye for anything out of place.  He was reasonably certain they must be nearly through the forest by now.  Sure, Nimreth was big but it didn’t go on forever…supposedly only a day’s ride to cross right through it.  To support his theory, the gloom of the woods started to lighten, and the trees around the path thinned somewhat so he wasn’t forever having to hold them out of his way. <br />
<br />
He wasn’t sure of Ukiria’s top speed, but he was convinced that she would be at least as fast as Kiria.  So perhaps with daylight and the end of the forest came another day and a half in the saddle, maybe even less, before reaching Lerona.  He was satisfied.<br />
<br />
<div align="center">* * * *</div><br />
Hunkered down in the shadows surrounding the Clearing, Jisvold closed his eyes to rest.  He was a good three hours ahead of the brat.  No steed could outpace a Black Brethren in his home territory.  Jisvold’s original plan had been simple.  Wound the plains rider with his first arrow, kill the steed with his second, and then have some fun watching the pale Huramesti die, perhaps using him for target practice to get him begging for his life…or better still, begging for his death.<br />
<br />
However, after thinking on it a bit while he was running, he came up with a big question mark.  What possible power does this Huramesti scum have to be able to ride such a rare creature.  Jisvold was no fool.  He had read about unicorns.  They were supposed to be the minions of Raer, the Steed and Companion to the Maker.  Jisvold didn’t believe in the gods of good, only in his own Evil One and HIS bonded minions.  But the few glimpses he had had of this nearly white steed, in itself uncommon among the bays and browns and blacks of Huramesti horses, convinced him that perhaps he was being a bit hasty.  He decided to wound and unhorse the Huramesti brat as planned, but to contrive a trap from the woven spider webbing he always carried.  He was pleased with the plan…trap the unicorn and torture the brat until he confessed how he held sway over this rare beast.  Jisvold enjoyed the picture of him subduing the unicorn…bringing it back to the forest camp of his clan… showing them how powerful that he, Jisvold, was.  That would certainly wipe the sneer off Gardorn’s face.<br />
<br />
With great skill, Jisvold fashioned a trap that was triggered by merely stepping on the ground under the tree.  The net held by the trap mechanism from falling would then let loose and drop upon its prey.  The dark elf walked carefully around the tree, making sure nothing would accidentally trip the mechanism.  His dark face beamed with evil anticipation.  He was satisfied that the trap would do as it was contrived to do.  Turning up the hood of his black cloak, he melted back into the forest edge embracing the Clearing and waited.<br />
<br />
<div align="center">* * * *</div><br />
The Clearing loomed ahead.  Patryll was content that this was the right spot to exit the Forest.  Personally, he hoped he never had to traverse it again.  He had never felt such unpleasant, even evil, vibrations as were present in those woods.  He leaned over and patted Ukiria’s neck, more to reassure himself of goodness than to encourage the unicorn.  Ukiria paid no attention, her ears flicking back and forth, searching for danger.  She stopped before fully entering the Clearing, and Patryll could not urge her forward.  He thought it unseemly to kick a near-godly being in the side, but he was getting impatient to be moving on and bringing relief to the villagers of Lerona.<br />
<br />
Finally, he jumped down and grabbed the bridle, pulling at the steed’s head until she reluctantly moved forward with him.  He felt it a small price to pay to walk the last few steps out of the Forest in order to get Ukiria to move at all.<br />
<br />
With the open plain in view just a hundred yards away, he hurried, anxious to be out of the Forest and riding like the wind to the stricken village.  He patted the baggage roll at the back of the saddle, reassuring himself that the potion was still there.  Paying less attention than he might, he started running, when the unicorn pushed him out of the way with her head and forged ahead in front of him.<br />
<br />
As he tried to sit up, disoriented by the push, two things happened at once.  An arrow went whizzing above his head, just about where his chest would have been had he been standing.  At the same time, an unearthly scream nearly shattered his eardrums.  He held his ears for a moment, as the scream faded into the still morning.<br />
<br />
Hastily, he jumped to his feet, only to see Ukiria snared in some kind of webbing.  She was well and truly caught, and her struggles served only to enmesh her more tightly in the webbing.  He ran forward, loosening his hunting knife as he did, with the thought of cutting the webbing and freeing her.<br />
<br />
A blow on the back of his shoulder spun him around as if he were a rag doll at the end of an elfin child’s whiplash game.  At first, his shoulder was numb and he thought perhaps he had inadvertently hit it when Ukiria had pushed him out of the way.<br />
<br />
Then the pain started, a tearing burning pain that spread from his neck down to his waist.  Any movement caused him agony.  Gritting his teeth, he turned and continued forward to the tree beneath which stood Ukiria, her flanks heaving, her forehoofs pawing the ground as much as the trap would allow.<br />
<br />
Another blow slammed into his right shoulder, and he almost fell.  But he couldn’t stop, he couldn’t let Ukiria be taken.  Perhaps, if he freed her, she would run to the village with the potion in her saddle roll.  He reached the web and slashed it just as another blow thudded into his thigh.  His legs buckled under him.  He bit his lip until the blood flowed and still reached up to slash the webbing.  Ukiria saw what he was doing and held still.  Another arrow went flying past the two of them, hitting the ground just beside the tree.  <br />
<br />
With one final slash, Patryll made the hole in the web big enough that Ukiria could free herself.  She jumped sideways and stood trembling as the dark elf stood up from his hiding place and aimed the notched arrow at her.  Patryll saw what he was doing and strained to get to his feet.  “No,” he screamed.  He threw his hunting knife as best he could, which startled the Kor brethren.  With blood running down both his arms, he managed to swing one arm over and dig into the pocket in his tunic.  He withdrew the leaf and threw it to the ground.  If he released Ukiria, she would have a chance to run the day and a half to get to the village.  He couldn’t say how he knew she would…he just knew.  It was worth his life to save the village…and Kiria.  Things were swimming in his vision now.  He fell forward on his knees, his arms dangling useless, ignoring the approach of the dark elf.<br />
<br />
Ukiria stood still, at the elf’s approach.  When the leaf hit the ground, she was surrounded by a blaze of white light, similar to the light that Patryll had observed when the dryad had come forward.  For some reason, he was not blinded this time.  Perhaps he was getting used to it, he thought irrationally.  However, the dark elf threw up his arms and cried out in pain.  His woods-trained eyes were extremely sensitive to light, and the flash blinded him.<br />
<br />
Still on his knees, the plains elf hung his head, trying desperately to raise it to say goodbye to Ukiria.  He felt himself slipping, losing grip on life, and he wanted his last glimpse to be of the beautiful steed his horse had become.  He was not even surprised that she was now a pure glowing white color…a color that made the eyes ache to watch for too long.  Her long silky mane was a darker silver, like the etched metal of silver chains, and her eyes were a brilliant silver blue. <br />
<br />
“Farewell, my Kiria,” he whispered.  “Run like the wind, holy unicorn, and bring the potion to the people of Lerona.  Know that your Patryll loves whatever is left of Kiria inside.”<br />
<br />
The beautiful unicorn bowed her head, nuzzling Patryll gently on the cheek.  He heard the words in his head, and was at last surprised.  “I do as you bid, my lord.”  The steed turned and sped out of the Clearing as fast as a ray of moonlight shining from space to earth.<br />
<br />
As she left the Clearing, the dark elf stirred, then sat up.  His face worked into a rage of disappointment.  Patryll read his own fate in the Kor brethren’s black eyes.  He shut his own eyes to await the killing blow.  Instead, he heard a thud and a grunt.  He opened his eyes in time to see the dark elf sliding to the ground with an arrow through his back.  It had been shot with such force that the shaft had penetrated through bone and organs, and the tip had emerged in the front.<br />
<br />
Patryll barely was able to get out of the way before the elf fell, dead by the time he hit the ground.  Wondering if he had another foe to fight, Patryll look around.  The pain throughout his body was beginning to throb so badly that he couldn’t concentrate.  He slumped to his side.  Moments or hours or weeks later—he had lost himself in the river of time—a voice with a Leronan accent drawled, “Are you alive, boy?”  He opened his eyes to stare into the face of a Huramesti hunter, an older man, with concern in his eyes and a small smile on his lips.<br />
<br />
“I am,” Patryll admitted, stifling a groan.  “Barely.”<br />
<br />
“We’ll have you up and about in no time, youngster,” the hunter said.  “Lay still and we’ll bring a litter to carry you to the village.”<br />
<br />
Patryll thought that might be a splendid idea.  He closed his eyes, but opened them at the hunter’s next words.  “We were looking for you to see if you had the potion.  You do, don’t you?”<br />
<br />
“Yes,” Patryll said painfully.  “But my horse has it in her saddle roll.  She is heading for the village right now.”<br />
<br />
“Horse!!  You mean that silver vision of Raer that I saw flying out of here like a pegasus?”<br />
<br />
Patryll smiled.  “That was my horse.”  He fainted.<br />
<br />
</font><div align="center"><font size="2">Birth of a Unicorn © 2006 by Sandra Bell</font><br />
<font size="2">All rights reserved.</font><br />
<br />
<i>(Another story will tell the tale of the battle for Lerona and the role that Patryll and Ukiria play in it.)</i></div><br />
<br />
